understanding of how crops grow and fruit ripens. Allegiance to them has frequently impeded open-minded investigation into how grapevines interact with the environment, thus limiting innovation in winegrowing. In Terroir and Other Myths of Winegrowing, Mark A. Matthews applies a scientist’s skepticism and scrutiny to examine widely held beliefs about viticulture. Is terroir primarily a marketing ploy that obscures understanding of which environments really produce the best wine? Is reducing yield an imperative for high quality grapes and wine? What does it mean to have vines that are balanced or grapes that are physiologically mature? Matthews explores and dissects these and other questions to debunk the myths of winegrowing that may be holding us back from achieving a higher wine quality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aTerroir. 0aViticulture. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh  aamerican wines.  acalifornia wines.  acreating fine wine.  acultivating grapes for wine.  acultivating winegrapes.  adebunking wine myths.  afine wine.  afood wine agriculture.  agrapevines.  agrowing fine wine.  agrowing grapes.  ahigh quality wine.  aquality wine.  arealities of winemaking.  aserious sommelier.  asommelier.  aterroir.  aviticulturalists.  aviticulture.  awine books.  awine grapes.  awine marketing.  awine myths.  awinegrapes.  awinegrowing.  awinemakers.  awinemaking myths.  awinemaking.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106675470 cprintz978052027695640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096200240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520962002423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/978